neighborhoods.name: East Cesar Chavez
neighborhoods.description: East Cesar Chavez is located on the north bank of the Colorado River and is bounded to the south by Lake Lady Bird and Festival Beach. The majority of the neighborhood is residential. Willow-Spence Streets Historic District is in the neighborhood and is part of the National Register of Historic Places. The neighborhood is diverse in its style of homes, businesses and residents. The neighborhood has a good combination of amenities for those looking for urban living or for nature seekers.

neighborhoods.name: Central East Austin
neighborhoods.description:
Central East Austin is an established Austin neighborhood dating back to the mid-Nineteenth Century. Historically this area was a central part of the city's African-American community. Many seniors and retirees have lived in their homes here for decades, but there has been an influx of newcomers including single young professionals, families, artists, and students attracted by the neighborhood's convenient location and inexpensive housing. Some of the rundown houses are being replaced by new construction, including new condos and housing developments, Which makes this neighborhood a great one for owning a rental property.

Although there is relatively little in the way of upscale shopping or dining here, new businesses are opening regularly, and other activities are available. If you're a picnic lover, you can go to Chestnut Park, which has a picnic area, BBQ pits, playground, and splash pad. There's also Bennu Coffee, one of the few 24-hour coffee shops in town, French Litigation Museum and the Austin Film Festival which both have low-cost film screenings.

neighborhoods.name: South River City
neighborhoods.description: South River City was developed in the late 19th and early 20th century to be Austin's first planned urban communities south of the Colorado River. The first two attempted settlements in present-day South River City were troubled by the lack of transportation with Downtown Austin. However, after the Congress Avenue Bridge was completed in 1910, it caused the neighborhood to boom in the 1920s and 1930s. The Victorian-era structures are what remained from the many single-family homes built back then.You could find some incredible investment properties in this neighborhood.

neighborhoods.name: North Panhandle
neighborhoods.description:
North Panhandle is a high-demand neighborhood and is located north of the Golden Gate Park and next to Divisadero Corridor. In this neighborhood, you’ll always have something to do as the neighborhood is central to everything and can be accessed within walking distance. If you’re unable to walk, there is easy access to the freeway, public transportation, and navigable bike routes.

The neighborhood also has lots of green space yet a lot of amenities, allowing residents to easily live without a car. You can grocery shop at the Lucky Center on Fulton and at the The Fallaetti Food at Broderick Place which has specialty deli goods.  There are plenty of hip restaurants, clubs, and shops to enjoy as well. You can easily connect with neighbors in this community either at Sunday’s Divisadero Famer’s Market or at the bi-monthly Divisadero Art Walk.

neighborhoods.name: Western Addition
neighborhoods.description:
Western Addition is a collection of small, multicultural neighborhoods united by a loose confederation of geography at the center of San Francisco.  Today, the Western Addition is predominantly working-class and is seen as the City's first multicultural neighborhood. The area includes the Fillmore, Japantown, Alamo Square and the Western Addition proper.  From the beautiful views at Alamo Square to the historic Fillmore area to the always changing Divisadero Street, you can experience several distinct moods in the space of a few blocks.  In 1948, San Francisco declared the Western Addition a slum and planned to tear it down in the name of urban renewal (or "urban removal” as it also became known for). New housing attracted young professionals, and the African-American community was pushed south toward Market Street.  

Among the locals, the area is known for its jazz age past, it's musically happening rich Fillmore neighborhood, the low rents of the area bordering the Tenderloin, the Eastern feel of Japantown, and the charm of the Painted Ladies in Alamo square.  The Jazz scene on Fillmore became very popular in this area, with the likes of Duke Ellington and Billie Holiday frequently playing clubs here. Close knit African-American church congregations were also joining together to worship on every block.  The Fillmore has always been viewed as the first full-fledged African-American community. Before World War II it was home to Japanese-Americans as well, but internment resulted in drastic changes leading to the arrival of Jewish immigrants and African-American GIs returning from the war.

neighborhoods.name: Haight Ashbury
neighborhoods.description:
Years ago, the Haight-Ashbury of San Francisco scene had a long-gone '60s and ‘70s hippie culture.  However, over time the Haight has changed.  But save for a few hippie memorabilia, today the Haight has a whole new vibe.  Although there are some fragments of flower-power, incense-burning, acid-dropping, peace-and-love-vibing era that can be purchased at smoke shops along the neighborhood, today the neighborhood is different. With exclusive boutiques, high-end vintage-clothing shops, second-hand stores, Internet cafés and hip restaurants having all settled in, this reinvented area stands out as one of San Francisco's commercial centers.  

What makes the Haight unique is its just-rolled-out-of-bed vibe during the day, which provides a perfect opportunity for lazing around in cafés and bookstores.  Weekends can get quite crowded with shoppers and brunch seekers during the day and club-goers at night. Neo-punks, club kids, fashionistas, tourists and neighborhood locals also fit in here, whether they have come to get a new piercing, grab a burrito or just enjoy some fun people-watching from a café.  But there are two distinct areas of the Haight: The Upper Haight, which stretches from Stanyan to Masonic, which is known as the shopping zone, though it deteriorates a bit where it stretches toward Golden Gate Park. While, the Lower Haight, roughly Divisidero to Webster is a more diverse neighborhood with a stony feel. While it has been an alternate nightlife hub for years, the Lower Haight has become a main attraction for DJs and ravers with an attraction to dance-music and clubs.

neighborhoods.name: Mission
neighborhoods.description: The Mission District, also commonly referred to as the “The Mission” was named for Mission Dolores in 1776. Although this is one of San Francisco’s oldest neighborhoods, it is known for having some of the hottest restaurants, shops and galleries. Neighborhoods of Bernal Heights and Potrero Hill boast some of the best weather in town with an abundance of sunshine. A great place to visit is Mission Dolores, 16th and Dolores streets, which is home to the oldest original intact mission in California and the city’s historic center. Throughout the District, there is a large number of murals which are decorating buildings, fences and walls. The Potrero Hill neighborhood is ideal for buying an investment property, as it is one of 11 historic districts in the city and is home to the second crookedest street in the city, Lombard being the first. In the 90’s, this neighborhood was home mostly to Latin American working-class families. However, in recent years, younger locals are flocking to the Mission for its hip bars and excellent taquerias. The cuisine in the Mission neighborhood, especially Mexican cuisine, might very well be the richest in a city that is already obsessed with food. Head to La Taqueria, a 50-year-old San Francisco institution that practically invented the local taco and that brags a long list of burrito styles. Make sure to try the taco dorado, a freshly deep-fried taco shell wrapped in a soft corn tortilla and filled with your choice of meat and all the extras you can add. Today, the Mission is home to the city’s hipster generation in addition to its fancy cupcakeries, cool music shops and boutique clothing stores. For an authentic experience, head toward 24th Street, or across Cesar Chavez toward 30th St. More than just a park, Dolores Park San Francisco is located in the heart of the the Mission. On a sunny day, the young come here to tan, hobnob, and take unbeatable views of the San Francisco bay and skyline. Don’t want to tan? Bring a picnic and a bottle of wine to enjoy the day and hang out.
